{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596363"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:12:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15405"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15405"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63575"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8096"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9133"},{"type":"tags","id":"9195"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20852"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63575"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a three month history of intermittent rectal bleeding. He has noticed bright red blood on the toilet paper after defaecation. There is no associated pain and he does not have any other symptoms apart from chronic constipation. Nothing abnormal is seen on visual inspection of the perineum until patient is asked to strain (Image). Digital rectal examination reveals no other abnormalities. Anoscopy shows enlarged vascular cushions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s stage of haemorrhoids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stage I","Stage II","Stage III","Stage IV","External haemorrhoids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003EStage II\u003C/strong\u003E haemorrhoids. These prolapse during defaecation but spontaneously reduce. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage I\u003C/strong\u003E haemorrhoids, which are internal haemorrhoids that may bleed but do not prolapse outside the anal canal.  \u003Cstrong\u003EStage III\u003C/strong\u003E haemorrhoids prolapse and require manual reduction. \u003Cstrong\u003EStage IV\u003C/strong\u003E haemorrhoids are permanently prolapsed and cannot be reduced. \u003Cstrong\u003EExternal haemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E occur below the dentate line and are typically painful rather than painless.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key features supporting Stage II classification are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPainless bleeding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo visible external abnormalities until the patient strains\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProlapse with straining\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEnlarged vascular cushions visible on anoscopy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemorrhoids are classified into four stages based on their degree of prolapse and reducibility","Stage II haemorrhoids are internal and may bleed and prolapse outside the anal canal"],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Feb 1;97(3):172-179. PMID: 29431977","Sun Z, Migaly J. Review of Hemorrhoid Disease: Presentation and Management. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2016 Mar;29(1):22-9. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1568144. PMID: 26929748; PMCID: PMC4755769","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21206"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21206"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yAimKvTNG6wM8M9lMcMCWnGvEkKU9k.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yAimKvTNG6wM8M9lMcMCWnGvEkKU9k.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T16:29:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T16:29:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8096"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63575"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","n